      "text": "The ambiguity of these places is certainly delightful, and a powerful connective experience. Nevertheless, it is important that each space be experienced as a distinct place, felt as one identifiable piece in a [[Place Network]]. The seamless flow into another place is then perceived as emotionally positive. If, on the other hand, the geometrical character (especially the nature of the boundaries) is blurred to such an extent that the spaces are not perceived as distinct places, a user is likely to feel confused, as if swimming in ambiguity. This unsettling experience occurs in many cases where, for example, the indoor-outdoor distinction is totally erased through a plate glass curtain-wall. The original A Pattern Language puts a great deal of emphasis on how to achieve this coherence successfully.",
